[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 Moves that aren't 3.d4"]
[Black "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 3.c3 Delayed alapin"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 Nf6 4. Be2 Nbd7
{ Black can't play Nxe4 yet because of Qa4+, but Nbd7 renews that threat. In some cases after Nc6 white can play d4-d5 and so the knight is more secure on d7. }
5. d3 { White should defends the e4 pawn } 5... g6
{ e6 is also playable but the bishop is stronger on the long diagonal } 6. O-O
Bg7 7. Nbd2 { Developing and protecting the e4 pawn so d4 becomes possible }
7... O-O 8. Re1 b6
{ If 9. d4 black can play Qc7  (among other moves)  and transpose into the 8. d4 Qc7 9. Re1 line. Otherwise, black is simply developing with a solid position and planning to eventually play d5. }
9. d4 Qc7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 Moves that aren't 3.d4"]
[Black "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 3.c3 Delayed alapin "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 Nf6 4. Be2 Nbd7
{ Black can't play Nxe4 yet because of Qa4+, but Nbd7 renews that threat. In some cases after Nc6 white can play d4-d5 and so the knight is more secure on d7. }
5. d3 { White should defends the e4 pawn } 5... g6
{ e6 is also playable but the bishop is stronger on the long diagonal } 6. O-O
Bg7 7. Nbd2 { Developing and protecting the e4 pawn so d4 becomes possible }
7... O-O 8. d4 Qc7
{ Also possible is cxd4 9. cxd4 e5 with approximately equal play. The problem with this is white can take on e5 removing the tension and without much imbalance it is harder to fight for the win. Black can develop his queen and bishop first, and play the ...cxd4 cxd4 e5 plan is usually still available for later if needed. }
9. d5
{ Removing the central tention quickly favors black: Black can play Re8 and e6 improving some of his pieces and removing some of white's pressure }
9... Re8 10. Re1 e6
{ If c4 black can take on d5 and he has powerful pieces and the outpost on e5 for his knight. }
11. dxe6 Rxe6
{ Black is at least equal here with pressure against white's position } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 Moves that aren't 3.d4"]
[Black "Sicilian: 2.Nf3 d6 3.c3 Delayed alapin "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 Nf6 4. Be2 Nbd7
{ Black can't play Nxe4 yet because of Qa4+, but Nbd7 renews that threat. In some cases after Nc6 white can play d4-d5 and so the knight is more secure on d7. }
5. d3 { White should defends the e4 pawn } 5... g6
{ e6 is also playable but the bishop is stronger on the long diagonal } 6. O-O
Bg7 7. Nbd2 { Developing and protecting the e4 pawn so d4 becomes possible }
7... O-O 8. d4 Qc7
{ Also possible is cxd4 9. cxd4 e5 with approximately equal play. The problem with this is white can take on e5 removing the tension and without much imbalance it is harder to fight for the win. Black can develop his queen and bishop first, and play the ...cxd4 cxd4 e5 plan is usually still available for later if needed. }
9. Re1
{ Other moves are possible for white, but black is doing fine in those as well. }
9... b6 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Qe2 cxd4
{ Now this plan is more favorable, black has improved his pieces more than white since move 8  (black has finished his development and white hasn't so opening the position favors black) }
12. cxd4 e5 13. dxe5
{ If white does nothing with the d pawn black has the option of exd4 with knight outposts on c5/e5 and the open e file. If white plays instead plays d5, black has pressure on the c file and the c5 square for his knight. }
13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Nf3 Rfd8
{ Black will soon either double up on the d file or play Rac8. He can also maneuver the knight to c5 via d7 if needed. Black has a lot of pressure here and has the better position. }
