[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7
{ Black blocks with the bishop so he could have smooth development. Nc6/Nd7 are also playable. }
4. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ 3. Bb5+ has helped black develop  (trades the bishops but develops black's queen)  but Bc8 was black's good bishop. Black can play Nc6 with Nf6 and g6+Bg7  (e6+Be7 is an alternative, which one is used depends on what white plays)  and O-O with easy play. }
5. O-O Nc6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Re1
{ This allows c4 before Nf6 but black still has counterplay even with white playing the Maroczy bind pawn structure with e4 and c4 with Nc3 }
8... g6 9. c4 Bg7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Nc2
{ This avoids trades as white has more space. Be3 is also possible but black has the same idea, with an extra possibility of capturing on d4.  or Ng4 }
11... Rfc8
{ Black is at least equal with coordinated pieces and active play on the queenside  (ideas include pushing the pawns forward there gaining space and/or Qd8 Nd7-Nc5)  . The c4 pawn can also sometimes be a target. }
