[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: 2.c3 Alapin and 2.d4"]
[Black "Alapin: 2.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks the e4 pawn forcing white to either advance the pawn, defend it of play a gambit. Advancing the pawn with e5 is the most common because the gambit should not sound here and defending the pawn is passive. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 { 5. d4 should transpose into 4. d4 } 5... Nb6 6.
Bb3 c4 7. Bc2 Qc7 8. O-O
{ White's main move is 8.Qe2, but White sometimes plays 8.0-0 to sacrifice a pawn. }
8... Nxe5 { Black accepts the pawn sacrifice. } 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 Qc7
{ Black is a pawn ahead and has a central pawn majority. If he manages to catch up on development, he will have a significant advantage. In the meantime, White has a big lead on development and has castled. White can fight for the initiative. }
11. d3 { White prepares to open the position.   11.d4  cxd3  is similar } 11...
e6 { Black prepares to develop his kingside. } 12. a4
{ White tries to destabilize Black's b6-knight, which was guarding his c4-pawn.   12.dxc4  Nxc4  is fine for Black   12.b3  is too slow.  12...cxd3  13.Qxd3  d5  gives Black a good position. }
12... cxd3
{ Black doesn't want to be forced to take on c4 with his queen. It is more favorable to trade now because White spent a tempo on a4. }
13. Qxd3 { White makes a queen-bishop battery. } 13... Be7
{ Black prepares to finish his development. Black can play ...f5 if he needs to castle. In the meantime, Black's king can hide behind his central pawns. }
14. Na3 a6 { Black prevents Nb5. } 15. a5
{ White secures the b6-square and chases away Black's b6-knight. } 15... Nd5
16. Nc4 { White attacks the b6-square. } 16... d6
{ Black prepares to finish his development with ...Bd7 and ...Bc6. Black can later play ...f5  (or ...Nf6)  in order to castle. This position is very unbalanced and both sides have winning chances. }
*

