[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks the e4 pawn forcing white to either advance the pawn, defend it of play a gambit. Advancing the pawn with e5 is the most common because the gambit should not sound here and defending the pawn is passive. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d5
{ g6 is a very dynamic way of playing, though white should be somewhat better if he is accurate. }
8. exd6 Qxd6
{ Black has equalized as he is very active. If White takes on d4 he gets an isolated queen pawn where black is ready to develop quickly and blockade it. Na3 is easily met with ...a6 and white is no more active than black. If white castles black can aim to trade white's active bishop with ...Be6 followed by rapid development. }
*

