1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6
{ 4...a6 is also good, aiming to play Nc6 without allowing Bb5. } 5. Bb5
{ This is more or less forced in order to not lose a tempo retreating the queen. }
5... Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. c4
{ White is aiming to play a maroczy bind. Black gets a superior maroczy bind here due to his bishop pair and the queen being vulnerable on d4 - after Nf6 g6 Bg7 and 0-0 the queen is vulnerable to discovered attacks from Bg7. }
7... Nf6
{ 7...f5 is a good alternative as 8.exf5 doesn't win a pawn as Qa5+ wins the pawn back. }
8. Nc3 g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Qd3 { White's queen gets off of the long diagonal. }
10... O-O 11. Nd4 Qb6 12. Rd1
{ 12.Be3 allows black a pleasant choice: 12...Qxb2  (this move is computer checked)  with a slightly better position   13.Nd5  almost allows white to equalize  or 12...Ng4 with easy equality. }
12... Ng4
{ Black is very active and is at least equal. Black intends to play Ne5. Black's queen can sometimes go to c5 and the rooks can come out quickly. If necessary black can trade Nd4 and white's queen by taking twice on d4. }
