1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ Some aggressive players play this, but it is inaccurate  (Nc3 first is better)  because it allows ...d5. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Nf6 { Black is playing a gambit. 3...Qxd5 loses time to Nc3. }
4. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Bd7 is also possible but Nbd7 is more ambitious, aiming to gain the bishop pair. }
5. c4
{ If white doesn't do this, black gets his pawn back and develops smoothly and white still has the somewhat weak e4 square. }
5... a6 6. Ba4 b5
{ This is not losing a pawn, black wins the d5 pawn if white takes. } 7. cxb5
Nxd5
{ Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. He has ideas of Nb6 and quick development and white taking on a6 is bad because of ...Bxa6. }
*

