[Black "Sicilian: 2.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4
{ In some cases this pawn structure favors white  (after Nf3 and d4)  but Black can prevent this plan and 2.c4 makes a hole on d4. }
2... Nc6
{ 2.e5 is also possible with an approximately equal position, but this is more flexible. Black is developing and controlling the weak d4 square. }
3. Nc3
{ Nf3 is also possible  (threatening d4 planning a maroczy bind)  but then black could play e5 with at least equality. }
3... g6
{ White hasn't played Nf3 in time to get his maroczy bind or force ...e5. Black prepares Bg7 putting the bishop on the long diagonal, also aiming at d4. }
4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Black has prevented d2-d4 and has a good position. One good plan is e6+Nge7  (to prepare to put a knight on d4 and support it with the other knight, not block the bishop, and maybe support ...d7-d5)  and 0-0. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: Other sidelines for white"]
[Black "Sicilian: 2.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4
{ In some cases this pawn structure favors white  (after Nf3 and d4)  but Black can prevent this plan and 2.c4 makes a hole on d4. }
2... Nc6 3. Nf3 e5
{ Black prevents d4 at the cost of a hole on d5. Both players have holes and the center seems closed, but black has the added option  (other than identical development of Nf6)  to play f7-f5 at some point. One simple plan for black is d6 and f5 with Nf6 and at least equality. }
