[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 { White commits his bishop too soon. } 2... e6
{ Black can block the diagonal and play against Bc4. Black also sometimes can play ...d5 with tempo. }
3. Nc3 { Developing and preventing ...d5 for now. } 3... a6 4. Nf3
{ Allowing b5, though white quickly developing. } 4... Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Be2 Nfd7
{ Black begins to pressure the weak e5 pawn. } 7. d4
{ 7.d3 is also possible but black's position is still much better as he has a great center, extra space and pressure on e5. Ideas include Nc6, Be7, 0-0 and Qc7 with easy development and pressure on the e5 pawn  (which can often be won) }
7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ or 8.Nxd4 Nxe5 with an extra pawn and a good position for black. } 8... Nc6
9. Qf4 Qc7 { Black can win the e5 pawn next. } *

