[Black "Sicilian: 2.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. g3 d5
{ White has neglected the center with 2. g3 so black strikes back there. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 { Gaining a tempo on the rook on h1 } 4. Nf3
{ If instead Qf3 black has a pleasant choice between exchanging queens for an endgame, developing with ...Nf6 or playing Qe6+ forcing white to move his king or block. In any case, black is doing fine. }
4... Bg4 { Pinning the knight and putting pressure on white's position } 5. Bg2
Qe6+ 6. Kf1 Nc6 { Developing and preparing Nd4 if needed } 7. h3
{ White has other possible moves but black has the same idea: Play Qd7 and finish his development with at least equality - because white can't castle. More aggressive ideas for black are also possible. }
7... Bh5 8. d3 Qd7
{ Transposes into 7. d3 Qd7 if white plays h3. The same plan of finishing development quickly with at least equality applies here as well. The idea behind Qd7 is to unblock e pawn to prepare e6/e5 to make development easier. }
