[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian: Other sidelines for white"]
[Black "Sicilian: 2.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. a3
{ White prepares to play b4, aiming to deflect the c5 pawn which controls d4. }
2... g6
{ Playing against white's idea. Black prepares to develop his bishop to the long diagonal and if white plays b4 black's bishop will be even more powerful. }
3. b4
{ White could play moves like Nc3 or Nf3, but then he would be playing a normal Sicilian down a tempo. If this happens black can develop normally with Bg7, Nc6, Nf6  (sometimes with d6)  0-0 and the d5 pawn break with good activity. }
3... Bg7 4. Nc3 Nf6
{ Inviting complications with 5.e5. These complications should favor black, as he is better developed. If black wants to avoid this, 4...b6 should offer simple equality. }
5. e5 Nh5 { The e5 pawn is a target and if necessary​ black can play Nf4. } 6.
bxc5
{ If instead 6.Nf3 black can play d6 and open the position. 6.Be2 is well met with Nf4. }
6... d6
{ Development is more important than material here. Black is far better developed. }
7. cxd6 exd6 8. Bc4 O-O
{ cxd5 is also possible, but this invites exd6 which would be a mistake. } 9.
Nf3
{ 9.exd6 would offer black excellent compensation for the pawn after Nf4 10.Qf3 Qxd6. }
9... dxe5 { Black's position is better. } *

