1. e4 c5 2. b3 g6 { Fighting for the long diagonal. } 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ Taking advantage of the pin. } 4... Bg7 5. e5
{ White could avoid playing e5, but without e5 black can develop quickly and sometimes play  (after Nc3)  Nxe4 due to the pin on Nc3. Black would also have the idea of playing d5. }
5... Nd5 6. d4
{ If white doesn't play actively black will be better due to his fast development and the e5 pawn being a target - which could be attacked by Nc6 Qc7 and d6. }
6... Qa5+
{ This forces a concession. 6...cxd4 should be enough with equality. } 7. Qd2
{ Both 7.Nbd2 or 7.c3 is well met with 7...cxd4 and black would have a much better position. }
7... Qxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxe5 { Black is a pawn ahead. } *

